I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve data from the API endpoint as the first step in the workflow.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the data_processing_validator requires data_processing_parser as a dependency, I'll first execute the parser tool to prepare the data for validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now that the parser has executed successfully, I'll proceed with the data validation step using the data_processing_validator tool. I'll use a default schema for validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array"
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {},
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since network_poster requires data_processing_transformer and integration_authenticator as dependencies, I'll first execute the data_processing_transformer tool.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now I'll execute the integration_authenticator tool, which is the second dependency for network_poster.

<tool_call>integration_authenticator
{
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now that all dependencies are satisfied, I'll execute the final network_poster tool to complete the API integration task.

<tool_call>network_poster
{
  "destination": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "data": {},
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {
    "auth_token": "token_557122"
  }
}
</tool_call>
